    <description>From publisher:&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Alesia 52 B.C., the Jurassian Hypothesis is a wargame (for 2 or 3 players) published by Canons en Carton, it includes two A3 color maps, 408 color counters a rules and scenarios booklet with historical notes.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Alesia, 52 B.C., the Jurassian Hypothesis does not pretend to provide a response to the question of finding the site of the decisive battle between Julius Caesar and Vercingetorix. Basing itself on the rules published in Vae Victis n&amp;deg;21, the game simply proposes a new sort of &amp;quot; What if ?&amp;quot; : how does one explain the sequence of events in the battle if it had occurred at the Jurassian site discovered by Andr&amp;eacute; Berthier? : Let's entertain ourselves by comparing the situation and the nature of the fighting with the two maps (the site of Alise and the site of Syam / Chaux-des-Crotenay) and let's forge an opinion. The game of history is a discipline which seems to have been invented for this, does it not ?&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
